you know , one of the great reasons in traveling and one of the joys in ethnography is to live with the people who still remember the old days . who still feel their past in the wind , touch it on the rain , taste it in the bitter leaves of plants .
just knowing that jaguar shame still travels beyond the milky way , or the meaning of the myths of the oldest of the inuit , or that in the himalayas , the buddhist still pursues the breath of the dharma , means to call the central revelation of anthropology into memory , that &apos;s the idea that the world in which we live , not in an absolute sense , but as a model of reality , as a result of a certain set of adaptations that are wasting our minds , in the same way , many generations .
and of course , we all share the same adaptability .
we &apos;re all born . we bring children to the world .
we go through initiation rituals .
we need to deal with the unstoppable separation of death , and so we shouldn &apos;t surprise ourselves that we all sing , dancing and art .
but what &apos;s interesting is the unique pitch of the song , the rhythm of the dance in every culture .
and it doesn &apos;t matter whether it &apos;s the penan in the forests of borneo , or the voodoo akolyths in haiti , or the warriors in the caisut-desert of northern kenya , the cures in the anden , or a caravan in the middle of the sahara . this is what happens to be the colleague i went to the desert a month ago , or even a yaker shepherd hanging on the qomaeda desert , everest , the mother of the world .
all of these people teach us that there are other ways of thinking , other ways of orienting the earth .
and that &apos;s an idea that , if you think about it , can only fulfill you with hope .
together , the world &apos;s countless cultures form a web of spiritual and cultural life that surrounds the earth and is as important for the sake of the earth as the biological web that you know as a biosphere .
you can think of this cultural web as an ethnosphere , and ethnosphere can be defined as the sum of all thoughts and dreams , myths , ideas , inspiration and intuitions that have been defined by the human imagination since the beginning of consciousness .
the ethnosphere is the great legacy of humanity .
it &apos;s the symbol of all the things we are and what we are capable of as an amazing white species .
and just like the biosphere was rejected very much , it happened with the ethnosphere -- only at even greater speed .
no biologist , for example , would argue that 50 percent or more of all species are about to extinct because it &apos;s just not true . and yet , this -- the most apocalyptic scenario in the field of biodiversity -- is barely what we know as optimistic scenarium in the field of cultural diversity .
and the key indicator of this is the extinction of languages .
when each of you was born in this room , 6,000 languages were talked on earth .
now a language is not just the vocabulary or a series of grammar creatures .
a language is expression of the human mind .
it &apos;s a means where the soul of a certain culture finds access to the material world .
every language is like an old-fashioned forest of the mind , a turning point , an idea , an ecosystem of spiritual possibilities .
and of these 6,000 languages , as we sit here in monterey , half of them are no longer whispered into the ears of children .
they &apos;re not taught anymore to children , which means that if nothing is done , they &apos;re actually dead already .
what could be more lonely than being surrounded by silence , one of the last people to be your language , no way to pass on the wisdom of the ancestors , or to expect children ?
and yet , this terrible destiny actually happens to someone on earth for about every two weeks , because every two weeks , an elderly person dies and takes the last syllable of an old language to the grave .
and i know some of you say , &quot; isn &apos;t it better ? &quot; wouldn &apos;t the world be a better place if we all talked just one language ? &quot; and i say , &quot; well , let &apos;s be yoruba . let &apos;s be cantonian .
let &apos;s be willii . &quot;
and then suddenly you would realize what it would be like if you couldn &apos;t speak your own language .
so today i want to take you on a journey through the ethnosphere , a short journey through the ethnosphere , to try to understand what &apos;s actually been lost .
now there are some of us who kind of forget that when i say , &quot; different possibilities of being , &quot; i mean really different possibilities of being .
for example , take this child of barasana in the northwest of the amazon , the people of anakonda , believe that they came up mythologically with the milk flow from the east in the belly of sacred snakes .
this is a people who don &apos;t cognitively distinguish between the colors of blue and green because the sky is equated to the forest that people depend on .
they have a strange language and a marriage rule called the linguistic exogamy : you have to marry somebody who talks a different language .
all of this is rooted in the mythological past , and the strange thing about these big houses , where , because of the misboats , six or seven languages , you &apos;re never hearing anyone who learns a language .
you just listen and then start talking .
or , one of the most fascinating tribes i &apos;ve ever lived with , the waorani in the northeast of ecuador , an amazing people who was first contacted peaceful in 1958 .
in 1957 , five missionary were trying to connect and made a severe mistake .
they threw shiny pictures of themselves out of the air , which we would rate as friendly gestures , and they forgot that these people from the rainforest in their lives had never seen anything two-dimensional .
they raised these photographs from the forest floor , tried to see behind the face or the figure , nothing , and concluded that this was business cards of the devil , and they killed the five missionary with the spear .
but the waorani didn &apos;t just kill outsiders with the spear .
they drilled through each other .
54 percent of the deaths were shot through drilling .
we followed geneaology eight generations and found two cases of natural death , and when we asked people about it a little bit , they admitted that one of the people had gotten so old that he died because of his age , and we still killed him with the spear .
but at the same time , they had a clear knowledge of the forest that was amazing .
their hunters could smell the urine of an animal from 40 steps away and determine what kind of animal this one was .
in the early &apos; 80s , i got a really amazing task when my professor at harvard asked me if i was interested in going to haiti and infiltrating the secret societies that were the foundation of the strength of duvalier and clay macoutes , and the poison that was used to make zombies safe .
to make sense of that conversation , of course , i had to know a little about this remarkable belief in the voodoo and voodoo is not a cult of the black magic .
on the contrary , it &apos;s a complex metaphysical view of the world .
it &apos;s interesting .
if i asked you to count the great world religions , what would you say ?
christianity , islam , buddhism , judaism or whatever .
