i &apos;m going to tell you a few things from my book that , i hope , are in harmony with other things that you &apos;ve heard , and i &apos;m going to try to create some connections if you haven &apos;t noticed them .
i want to start with what i call official dogma .
the official dogma of what ?
the official belief set of all western industrialized societies .
the official dogma works like this : if our goal is to maximize the common well-being of our citizens , it &apos;s especially through maximizing the freedom of the individual .
the reason for that is that freedom is good in itself , valuable , meaningful , an intangible assumption for human beings .
if people have freedom , each of us is about doing the things that maximize our public good and nobody has to decide for us .
the way to maximize freedom is to maximize choice .
the more choices people have , the more freedom they have , and the more freedom they have , the more common they have .
this is , i think , so deeply anchored in our water supply that nobody would ever mind .
and it &apos;s also deeply rooted in our lives .
i &apos;m going to give you some examples of what gives us modern progress .
this is my supermarket . this is not a big one .
i just want to say a little bit about salatdressing .
