the work of the interpreting .
music as a language .
in the description of my talk , i write that as a interpreter , i &apos;m a translator , so in english , i understand .
interprets are translators of the written notes in clinical music .
that as a translator , you have to understand not only the word for word &quot; text &quot; into a different language , but you have to understand the deeper sense of words and word bias to make it a meaningful translation , anyone knows what to do with foreign languages .
already from german to english , it can require more knowledge , even if you &apos;re talking about poetry or even about poetry .
but it &apos;s alien to layman what we do to musicians with our music language .
as a interpreter of a piece of music , i first have just the written notes .
you think the composer has written into the notes exactly everything he came up with .
in fact , the notes are very vague and inaccurate .
these notes are about as accurate or inaccurate as a verbal , even though very seemingly peniculous , description of a landscape .
because in this verbal landscape description , the smell of flowers is not to smell the degree of the founder , not to hear the column of the wind , not to feel .
that means the interpret has to translate these unprecedented views of emergency into another , which is audible , concrete , non-verbal music language .
today i want to translate to you what else i &apos;m using musically , which is interpreting , again , into a verbal language .
so basically , a translation of translation .
so i prefer to do the whole thing in german , because if i had to translate it back into english , it would be equally important for me to translate the translation of translation .
so the one that music works for me is similar to spoken word .
the notes that written are the function of the letters of a script .
so it &apos;s not enough to just learn to read notes and press the keys on the piano or the right place on a violin string .
because that would be just the letters you learned to paint .
you can only see the meaning of the letters if you can see the language .
so for the learning process of music , at least as long as it is for spoken word .
now , there are also exhibitions whether you learn it for practice , you just passively understand it , or you can also talk to the musical mother language .
the work of the interpret starts similar to a theater director .
after you first chose a piece of play , because you &apos;re excited about it , you study the origin of composition .
you collect information about the piece in the secondary literature .
you read in the letters , the dials , the notes , or whether there are words , the ideas of composers themselves .
you study the works he composed before and after .
you compare it .
the reasons to write it .
how and what did he feel ?
what were its circumstances , like society and politics ?
i &apos;m all interested in that .
you think into that time by , for example , looking at contemporary images or reading literature .
but over time , you also have a rich knowledge for the composer you play more often , and it &apos;s easier for you to think in and feel like you .
the composer is becoming more and more for your friend to live with .
his cause of writing the piece is becoming more and more to my personal cause of playing it .
now that the notes are everything but an accurate record of the cause of the composer , but only a framework , i &apos;m now turning this scaffolding to restore it with meaning and meaning .
i then say with my own words about what might be written between this scaffolding .
i play games explaining what these notes might have .
now for me and for the composers at the time and what they might mean for him today .
every note , every phrase , every phrase , gets a sense of it because i feel it myself because it comes from my personal jar .
it has to be coherent for me in this room and now , otherwise i can &apos;t convince my audience that this is my cause .
it &apos;s always a very happy concert over and over again if i can have the experience , the piece that i &apos;ve worked out for so long in advance , how to experience .
how you reexperience a happy new day , although always with the same rituals of life , get up , breakfast , going to work , i &apos;m doing the same piece over and over again .
i grew back a day older , which changes seasons , my pulse goes slower at night than in the morning , in a concert room , takes longer , the sound comes back than at home .
i take the breathing true of the audience , consciously or unconsciously .
all of this affects me , and all of this also affects my experience with composition .
it &apos;s quite wonderful when i stand on stage with a duo partner and we have the same wavelength .
then the same thing happens as a good , excited conversation .
you bring a new idea in , and anyway , it &apos;s answered with a reaction .
it &apos;s exciting because then things that we didn &apos;t try and do and which you can &apos;t sample either .
it &apos;s a lot of fun to make music that way , and you &apos;ve experienced how music communicates alive .
so every concert is a different concert .
i &apos;m never going to play anything like this moment .
i can &apos;t play today as much as i can in 20 years .
i &apos;m going to have more life experience than i do today , and so my palette of music will have much more color nuances , emotions and sentiments than it is today .
certainly , i &apos;m going to throw out some color pots as well , but get new ones .
