he spoke in a very hot and social note about yo-yo ma and hillary clinton , and how the dodgers would never get into the baseball world series , and all of this because of the first violin passage in the last sentence by beethoven &apos;s fourth symphony .
we came up with the theme of music , and a few days later i got an email saying nathaniel was interested in my own education .
i have to mention that nathaniel was rejecting medical care because he had already been treated with electric shocks and thorazine and handcuffs , a trauma that pursued him all his life .
as a result , he &apos;s now particularly vulnerable to these schizophrenic stages , which are sometimes so bad , and he disappears for days , going around the streets of skid row , always exposed to this horror and the torture jellyfish of his own mind .
and in the same way , nathaniel was at the same time that we started our first lesson in walt disney art hall , and he had this irre flatter in his eyes and worked completely out .
he talked about invisible demons and smoke and how somebody wanted to poison him in his sleep .
i was afraid , not opinion , but i was afraid that i could lose him , that he could sink into one of his states , and that i could destroy his relationship to the violin if i started talking about pitches and arpeggios and other exciting forms of didactic self-educators .
so i just started playing .
i played the first sentence by beethoven &apos;s violin concert .
and as i was playing , i noticed that in nathanian &apos;s eyes , a complete change was happening .
it was like standing under the impact of an invisible doctor , a chemical reaction whose catalyst was my game .
nathaniels manic anger turned into understanding that quiet curiosity and courage .
and as through a miracle , he took his violin and he started playing some clips of violin concerts , and then he asked me to end them : menu son , tshaikowski , sibelius .
we then started talking about music , from bach to beethoven , brahms , bruckner and all the other bs , from bartok to esa pekka salons .
and i realized that he had not just an encyclopedic knowledge about music , but he connected it to a close personal relationship .
he talked about her with a passion and an understanding that i used to know only about my colleagues in the philharmony of los angeles .
by playing music and talking about music , this paranoid , confused man who had just moved through the streets of los angeles , a loving , educated , excellent , trained musician in juilliard .
music is medicine . music changes us .
for nathaniel , music means mental health .
because music allows him to reform his thoughts and delusions with his imagination and creativity into something real .
and so he escapes his torture states .
i understood that this is the nature of art .
that &apos;s why we make music : so that we can do something that &apos;s deep inside all of us , our feelings , through our artistic lens , can actually shape through our creativity .
and the reality of that expression is that everybody reaches us , and moves , inspired and united .
in nathaniel &apos;s case , the music brought him back to a community of friends .
the redemption of music brought him back to a family of musicians who understood his talent and paid attention to him .
and i &apos;m going to keep making music with nathaniel , whether it &apos;s in the walt disney mind , hall or skid row , because he reminds me of why i became a musician .
