today i &apos;m going to talk to you about energy and climate .
and this may surprise you something , because my full-time work at the foundation is all about vaccines and seeds , about the things we need to invent and deliver to make the poorest two billion a better life .
but energy and climate are extremely important for these people , in fact , more important than anyone else on the planet .
climate degradation means that their strings will not grow over many years , we will not rain too much or too little , and things will change the way their fragile environment can &apos;t change .
this leads to starvation deaths . it leads to uncertainty . it leads to riots .
so , climate change is going to be terrible for you .
and also , the energy cycle is very important for them .
in fact , if you could only reduce the price from one thing , to reduce poverty would be energy at far the most effective .
well , the energy cycle fell over time .
in fact , the progress society is based on energy advances .
kohler evolution was driving the industrial revolution , and even in the 20th century , there was a rapid case of electricity , and that &apos;s why we have refrigerators , climate conditioners , we can make modern materials and do so many things .
so we &apos;re in a wonderful situation with electricity in the rich world .
but if we reduce the price -- let &apos;s cut the price down -- we hit a new barrier , and this barrier is related to co2 .
co2 warms the planet , and co2 equation is actually quite clear .
they accuse the emitted co2 that leads to temperature increases , and that temperature increases has some very negative consequences , effects on the weather , and perhaps worse , the indirectly that the natural ecosystems can &apos;t adapt to change that rapid , and so whole systems collapse .
well , the exact relationship between a carbon rise and the result of that is temperature change and where others are , there are some ambiguity , but not very many .
and there &apos;s certainly ambiguity about how bad these will follow , but they &apos;re going to be extremely bad .
i asked the top scientists a few times , &quot; do we really have to get down to zero ?
isn &apos;t it enough to half or a quarter ? &quot;
the answer is , until we get close to zero , the temperature will continue to rise .
so it &apos;s a big challenge .
