a few years ago , here at ted , peter skillman introduced a design competition called &quot; the marshmallow challenge . &quot;
the idea is pretty simple . four teams have to build the largest possible free structure with 20 spaghetti , about a meter tape , about a meter of thread and a marshmallow .
the marshmallow has to be on top .
and , although it seems really simple , it &apos;s actually really hard because it urges people to work together very quickly .
and so i thought that was an interesting idea , and i turned it into a design workshop .
it was a huge success .
since then , i &apos;ve done about 70 workshops around the world with students , developers and architects , even with ctos of fortune 50-company , and there &apos;s something about this task that gives deep impressions into the nature of collaboration , and i want to share with you some of them .
most people usually start orienting themselves in terms of the task .
they talk about what it &apos;s going to look like , they run around .
then you spend a little bit of time in planning and organization , sketching and putting spaghetti out .
they spend most of their time in assembling constantly growing structures .
and finally , just before you don &apos;t have time , somebody takes the marshmallow , and you put it gently on the top , step back , and &quot; ta-da &quot; ! admire your work .
but then what happens almost always is that the ta-da is becoming a uh-oh because the weight of the marshmallows causes the whole thing to bend and fall .
there are a number of people who have much more &quot; uh-oh &quot; moments than others , and among the worst , fresh bwl graduates .
they lie , they cheat , they &apos;re confused and they &apos;re really drunk .
and of course , there are teams who have much more ta-da shapes , and under the best , fresh graduates of kindergarten .
and that &apos;s pretty amazing .
as peter told us , they &apos;re not only producing the highest towers , but they &apos;re also the most interesting structures of all .
what you might ask is , how is that ? why is that ? what about them ?
and peter says , &quot; none of the kids spend time being the spaghetti gmbh . &quot;
they don &apos;t spend time in power fighting .
but there &apos;s another reason .
and that is that bwl students were trained to find the right plan , ok ?
and then realizing it .
what happens then when you put the marshmallow on the top , you don &apos;t have time , and what happens ?
it &apos;s a crisis .
sounds familiar , what ?
what kindergarten kids do differently is they start with the marshmallow and build prototypes , successful prototypes , always with the marshmallow at the top , so they have a multi-fold chance to fix bloody prototypes .
constructors recognize this kind of collaboration as a core of an iterative process .
and with every trial , kids get immediate feedback about what works and what doesn &apos;t work .
so the performance of working with prototypes is a lot -- but let &apos;s see how different teams act .
most of them are about 50 inches , bwl students create half of them , lawyers a little more , but not much , kindergarten children are better than adults .
who &apos;s most successful ?
architects and engineers , fortunately .
one foot is the highest thing i &apos;ve seen .
and why ? because they understand triangles and self-amplifying geometric patterns are the key to building stable structures .
ceos is a little over average . but this is where it gets interesting .
if you put an executive administrator on the team , they get significantly better .
it &apos;s incredible . you look around and you see , &quot; this team will win . &quot;
you can predict that . why is that happening ?
because they have special skills of processing .
they lead the process , you understand it .
and that team that rules and looks at work will significantly improve the performance of the team .
specialized skills and processing skills and their combination lead to success .
if you have 10 teams that are typical , you get about six that have stable structures .
now i tried something interesting .
i thought we &apos;d bring the poker operation in a minute .
so i offered a $ 10,000 prize in software for the winners .
what do you think happened to these design students ?
what was the result ?
this is what happened . not one team had a stable structure .
if anyone had built a three-inch construction , they would have carried the price home .
so isn &apos;t it interesting that high competitions have a strong effect ?
we repeated this exercise with the same students .
what do you think happened now ?
now they understood the advantage of the prototyping .
so from the same bad team , one under the best .
they produced the highest construction in the least time .
so there are profound lessons for us , about nature of drive and success .
you might ask : why would somebody actually spend time creating a marshmallow challenge ?
the reason is , i create digital tools and processes to help teams create cars , video games and visual games .
and what the marshmallow challenge does is it helps them identify hidden assumptions .
because frankly , every project has its own marshmallow .
the challenge is to have a shared experience , or a common language , or basic , to build the right prototype .
and that &apos;s the value of this experience , this simple exercise .
and those of you who are interested in it can visit marshmallowchallenge.com .
it &apos;s a blog where you see the marshmallows being built .
there &apos;s a step-by-step manual there .
you find crazy examples from around the world , how people optimize and retrain the system .
there are also world records .
and the basic lesson , i think , is that construction is actually a committing sport .
it demands that we &apos;re all doing our senses on the task and that we &apos;re using our thinking optimal , like our feelings and our doing , in the challenge that we face .
and sometimes a small prototype of this experience is all it takes to get us from a uh-oh to a ta-da moment .
and that can make a big difference .
thank you .
