everybody &apos;s talking about happiness today .
i &apos;ve had some people count the number of books that were published with happiness in the title of the last five years , and they &apos;ve spent about 40 on it , and there &apos;s much more .
there &apos;s a tremendous wave of interest in happiness among researchers .
there &apos;s a lot of happiness coaching .
everybody would like to make people happier .
but despite all this tide of work , there are several cognitive traps that make it almost impossible to think about happiness .
and my talk today will be mostly about these cognitive traits .
this is true of layman thinking about their own happiness , and it &apos;s true of scientists thinking about happiness because it turns out we &apos;re just as confused as any other person .
the first of these fall is a contradiction to admit complexity .
it turns out that the word happiness is just not a useful word anymore because we apply it to too many different things .
i think there &apos;s a certain meaning that we could constrain it to , but by and large , that &apos;s something we need to give up , and we &apos;re going to have to take on the complicated view of what well-being is .
the second trap is a confuse of experience and memory : basically , it &apos;s between happiness in its life and being happy about his life or his life .
and these are two very different concepts , and they &apos;re both together in the idea of happiness .
and the third one is the concentration illusion , and that &apos;s the unfortunate fact that we can &apos;t think about a fact that affects well-being without distorting its meaning .
i mean , this is a real cognitive trap .
there &apos;s just no way to get it right .
now i &apos;d like to start with an example of somebody who had a question and answer session after one of my lectures that reported a story . &#91; unclear &#93; he said he heard a symphony , and it was absolutely glorious music , and at the end of the recording , there was a terrible circling sound .
and then he added in , really quite emotional , that ruined the whole experience .
but it didn &apos;t .
what it ruined was the memories of the experience .
he had the experience .
he had had 20 minutes of glorious music .
they didn &apos;t count because he was left with a memory , the memory was ruined , and the memory was all he had to get .
what this really tells us is that we could think about ourselves and other people in the sense of two kinds of self .
there &apos;s a living self that lives in the present and knows the present is able to experience the past , but has basically just the present .
it &apos;s the living self that the doctor asks -- you know , when the doctor asks , &quot; does it hurt now when i touch you here ? &quot;
and then there &apos;s a memory self , and the memory itself is that counting and getting the story of our lives upright , and it &apos;s the one that the doctor promises by asking the question , &quot; how did you feel recently ? &quot;
or &quot; what was your journey to albania ? &quot; or something like that .
these are two very different units , the living self , and the memory itself , and the two of them to confuse is part of the immense terms of happiness .
well , the memory itself is a storyteller .
and this really starts with a fundamental reaction to our memories -- it starts immediately .
we don &apos;t just tell stories when we get to tell stories .
our memory tells us stories , which means what we can keep from our experiences is a story .
and let them start with an example .
there &apos;s an old study .
these are real patients who sign themselves to a painful procedure .
i &apos;m not going to go into the details . it &apos;s no longer painful today , but it was painful when this study was done in the 1990s .
they were asked to report their pain every 60 seconds .
and here are two patients . these are their records .
and they &apos;re asked , &quot; who of both of them suffered more ? &quot;
and that &apos;s a very simple question .
patient b clearly suffered more . his gut reflection was longer , and every minute of pain , the patient a had patient b and more .
but now there &apos;s another question : &quot; how much did these patients think they were suffering ? &quot;
and here &apos;s a surprise .
and the surprise is that patient a had a much worse memory of the gut reflection than patient b .
the stories of gut reflections were different , and because a very critical part of the story is how it ends .
and none of these stories are very building or great -- but one of them is this clear ...
but one of them is much worse than the other .
and the one that was worse was where the pain was at the very end of its peak . it &apos;s a bad story .
how do we know ?
because we asked these people about their gut reflection , and also much later , &quot; how bad was the whole thing ? &quot;
and it was much worse for a than b in memory .
well , this is a direct conflict between the living self and the memory of itself .
from the living self &apos;s point of view , b had a worse time .
now , what you could do with patient a , and we actually did clinical experiments , and it &apos;s been done , and it works , actually , you could extende the patient &apos;s gut reflection by just letting the tube in there without shaking too much on it .
that &apos;s going to lead the patient to suffer , but just a little bit less than they did before .
and if you do that for a few minutes , you &apos;ve been doing that , that the living self is worse off of a patient , and you &apos;ve done that memory itself from patients is much better off , because now you &apos;ve given patient a better story about your experience .
what does a story look like ?
and this is true of the stories that memory delivers us , and it &apos;s true of the stories we invent .
what excites a story is turnarounds , meaningful moments and ends .
end is very , very important , and in this case , dominated the end .
well , the living self lives its lives continuously .
it has moments of life , one after another .
and you ask , what happens to these moments ?
and the answer is really simple . they &apos;re lost forever .
i mean , most of the moments of our lives -- and i &apos;ve calculated this -- you know , the psychological present is true of about three seconds , which means , you know , there are about 600 million of them in a lifetime . in a month , there are about 600,000 . most of them don &apos;t leave a trace .
most of you are completely ignored by remembering yourself .
and yet , you get the impression that you should count that what happened during these moments of life has happened our lives .
it &apos;s the limited resource we use while we &apos;re in the world .
and how we would use them seemingly important , but that &apos;s not the story that keeps remembering itself from us .
so we have the memory itself and the living self , and they &apos;re really quite different .
the biggest difference between them is dealing with time .
from the perspective of living , even if you have a vacation and the second week is just as good as the first week , the second vacation is twice as good as the one-week vacation .
that &apos;s not how it works for memory itself .
for the memory of self , a two-week vacation is barely better than the one-week vacation , because there are no new memories added .
they didn &apos;t change the story .
and that &apos;s how time is actually the critical variable that distinguishes a memory itself from a living self , has very little impact on this story .
well , memory itself makes more than remembering and telling stories .
it &apos;s actually the one that makes decisions , because if you have a patient who , say , had two gut reflections in two different surgeons and decides which to vote , the one who chooses who has the memory that &apos;s less bad , and that &apos;s the surgeon who &apos;s going to be chosen .
the living self has no voice in that choice .
we don &apos;t actually choose between experiences . we choose between memories of experiences .
and even when we think about the future , we don &apos;t usually think about our future as experiences .
we think about our future as previous memories .
and basically , you can look at this , you know , as a tyranny of memory self , and you can think of the memory self as one that kind of draws the living self through experiences that don &apos;t need the living self .
i think the impression that when we do vacation is very often the case , that means we make vacation white in the service of remembering ourselves .
and that &apos;s a little bit hard to justify , i think .
i mean , how much do we consume about our memories ?
that &apos;s one of the explanations that &apos;s been given to the dominance of memory itself .
and when i think about it , i think of a vacation that we did a few years ago in antarctica , which was clearly the best vacation i had ever had , and i think a lot of times in relation to how often i think of other vacation .
and i &apos;ve probably been through this three-week journey from my memories , i would say for about 25 minutes in the last four years .
now , if i had ever opened the folder with the 600 pictures in it , i would have spent another hour .
