there seems to be a disagreement .
well , i may be a little extreme , you know , how little appetite i have on the toes of memories , but even if you make more of them , there &apos;s a real question . why do we give memories so much weight in the course of the weight that we give experiences ?
so i want you to think about a thought experiment .
imagine your next vacation , you know , at the end of vacation , all of your images are devastated , and you get an amnesiac drug so you &apos;re not going to remember anything .
well , would you choose the same vacation ?
and if you chose another vacation , there &apos;s a conflict between your two kinds of self , and you have to think about how you decide this conflict , and that &apos;s really not obvious at all , because if you think about time , in the sense that you get an answer , and if you think about memories , you could get another answer .
why we &apos;re looking for the vacation that we &apos;re looking for is a problem that we have with a choice between the two species of self .
well , the two kinds of self are recording two terms of happiness .
there are actually two concepts of happiness that we can use , one per self .
so you can ask : how happy is the living self ?
and then you would ask : how happy are the moments of the living self ?
and they &apos;re all -- happiness for moments is a pretty complicated process .
what are the emotions that can be measured ?
and , by the way , we &apos;re now able to get a pretty good idea about the happiness of the living self over time .
if you ask about the happiness of the memory self , it &apos;s a very different thing .
that &apos;s not about how happy one person lives .
it &apos;s about how satisfied or pleased the person is when they think about their lives .
very different term .
anyone who doesn &apos;t distinguish these terms will mess up exploring happiness , and i &apos;m part of a lot of researchers on well-being who have beaten up exploring happiness in this way .
the distinction between the happiness of the living self and the happiness of the memory self has been recognized in the last few years , and now you &apos;re trying to measure the two separate .
the gallup organization has a global survey where more than half a million people have been asked questions about what they think about their lives and what they &apos;ve experienced . and there have been other efforts in the direction .
so in the last few years , we &apos;ve been starting to learn about the happiness of the two kinds of self .
and the main lesson we &apos;ve learned , i think , is that they &apos;re really different .
you can know how satisfied somebody is with their life , and that really doesn &apos;t teach them much about how happy they live and vice versa .
just to give you an idea of the correlation , the correlation is about .5 .
what that means is that if you met somebody , and you were to tell them , oh , your father is a two-meter man , how much would you know about your size ?
well , you would know something about its size , but there &apos;s a lot of insecurity .
they have so much uncertainty .
when i tell you that somebody has ordered their life at an eight-scale scale of 10 , they have a lot of insecurity about how happy he is with their living self .
so the correlation is small .
we know something about what the happiness of the happiness itself determines .
we know that money is very important , goals are very important .
we know that happiness means mostly to be satisfied with people we like , to spend time with people we like .
there are other pleasure , but that &apos;s dominant .
so if you want to maximize the happiness of the two kinds themselves , you &apos;re going to do very different things at the end .
the conclusion i &apos;ve said here is that we should not really think of happiness as a replacement for well-being .
it &apos;s a completely different term .
well , very briefly , another reason we can &apos;t clearly think about happiness is that we don &apos;t look at the same things when we think about life and when we actually live .
so if you ask the simple question of how happy people are in california , they &apos;re not going to get the correct answer .
if you ask that question , you think that people in california have to be happier if they live in ohio , say .
and what happens is that when you think about life in california , you think about the difference between california and other places , and that difference is , say , in climate .
well , it turns out that climate is not very important for the living self , and it &apos;s not even very important for the thinking self that decides how happy people are .
but because the thinking self is responsible , you can end up -- some people could end up moving to california .
and it &apos;s kind of interesting to pursue what happens to people who move to california hoping to get happier .
well , your living self will not get happier .
we know that .
but one thing that &apos;s going to happen . you &apos;ll think you &apos;re happier , because if you think about it , you &apos;ll be reminded about how terrible the weather was in ohio , and you &apos;ll feel that you made the right decision .
it &apos;s very difficult to think about well-being , and i hope i &apos;ve given you a sense of how difficult it is .
