i &apos;m jane mcgonigal . i design video games .
i &apos;ve been developing online games for 10 years , and my goal for the next decade is to make it as easy to save the world in reality as it is to save in online games .
i have a plan for it . i want to convince more people to spend more time playing bigger and more great games .
we &apos;re currently spending three billion hours a week playing online games .
some of you may think , &quot; that &apos;s a lot of time for games . &quot;
maybe a little too much time when you think about how many problems we have to solve in the real world .
but in fact , my research at the institute of the future is exactly the opposite .
three billion hours a week is not nearly enough to solve the most urgent problems in the world .
in fact , i &apos;m convinced that if we want to survive the next century on the planet , we need to dramatically increase that time .
i calculated that the time that i took is 21 billion hours of play time a week .
this seems a little defense first , so i &apos;ll repeat it to make it work : if we want to solve problems like hunger , poverty , climate change , global conflicts and obesity , i think we need to try to play online for at least 21 billion hours a week to the end of the next decade .
no , i &apos;m really serious about it .
why ? this picture pretty much describes why i think games are so vital to the survival of the human species in the future . seriously .
this is a portrait of photographer phil toledano .
he wanted to capture the feelings of playing . so he &apos;s built a camera before the players .
this is one of the classic expressions of play .
if you &apos;re not a player , you might escape some of the nuances in this picture .
you &apos;re probably seeing this sense of urgency , a little scared , but also external concentration , very deep into solving a really difficult problem .
if you play too , you can see some nuances here that are zoomed up , and the mouth is a sign of optimism . the eyebrows are surprising .
this is a player standing on the edge of what &apos;s called an epic victory .
oh , you know that . ok . good . so we have some players here .
one epic victory is a result that &apos;s so overwhelmed that they didn &apos;t know it was possible before .
it was almost beyond the imagination .
and when they do it , they &apos;re shocked that they &apos;re actually capable of doing something like this . this is an epic victory .
this player is standing in front of an epic victory .
and this is what we need to see on millions of faces of problem-solvers around the world when we take the barriers of the next century , the face of those who are facing all the sights on the edge of an epic victory .
well , unfortunately , we see this face in real life when we face difficult problems .
