that &apos;s a problem that many players have .
we think we &apos;re not as good as we are in reality .
and i don &apos;t just mean less successfully , even though that &apos;s part of it .
we &apos;re doing more in games . i mean , i mean , in the context of motivation to do something significant , inspired to work with each other .
when we &apos;re in a game world , i think many of us are turning into our best version , at any given time and immediately helpful to try to solve the problem , as long as it takes , to try it again .
and in reality , when we fail , when we hit obstacles , we often feel different .
we feel overwhelmed . we feel defeated . we feel threatened , maybe depressed , frustrated or cynical .
we never have these feelings when we play games , and in games , they just don &apos;t exist .
and that &apos;s what i wanted to study as a ph.d. student .
why is it impossible in games to think that you couldn &apos;t just do everything ?
how can we transmit these feelings from games into reality ?
so i looked at games like world of warcraft that give the ideal environment to collaborative problem solving .
and i &apos;ve noticed a few things that make the epic victories possible in online worlds .
so , first of all , when you get into one of these online games , especially at world of warcraft , there are a lot of different characters who are willing to trust you a global mission , and that &apos;s immediately available .
but not just any mission , but a mission that fits perfectly to its current level in the game , right ?
so they can do that .
you never get a task you can &apos;t solve .
but always at the edge of their skills , so they have to stand up , but there &apos;s no unemployment in world of warcraft .
you &apos;re not sitting around turning . there &apos;s always something important to do .
