so to tell you about that tension , i have to first know that i &apos;m a big fan of the founding fathers .
i know they were raced , i know they were sexist , but they were great .
i think they were so brave and so strong , and so radical in what they did that i would look at the mallet of the malignant musical 1776 every few years , and it &apos;s not because of the music that &apos;s absolutely forgotten .
it &apos;s because of what happened to the founding fathers in 1776 .
the founding fathers , from my point of view , were the original anatomical activists , and that &apos;s why .
what they proved was an anatomical concept , and they replaced it through another that was radically and radically beautiful and 200 years for us .
as you all remember , our founding fathers rejected the concept of monarchy , and the monarchy was based on a very simplified concept of anatomy .
the rulers of the old world had no concept based on dna , but they had a concept of birth on it .
they had a concept of blue blood .
they were the notion that people who had political power should have this political power because of the inherited blood line from grandfather to son and so on .
the founding fathers turned this idea back and replaced it through a new anatomical concept , and this concept said that all people were created equal .
they niveled the field of play , and they decided that anatomically , they counted the similarities , not the differences . and that was very radical .
now they did that in part because they were part of an education system where two things grew together .
democracy grew in , but at the same time science grew in .
if you look at the story of the founding fathers , you realize that many of them were very interested in science , and they were interested in a concept of a natural world .
they went away from explanations of supernatural ways , and proven things like a supernatural concept of power , back where transmission is based on a very vague concept of birth .
they moved to a natural concept .
and if you look at , for example , the declaration of independence , they talk about nature and the god of nature .
they don &apos;t talk about god and god &apos;s nature .
they talk about the power of nature to tell us who we are .
and as part of that , they gave us a concept that was about anatomical common .
and they &apos;ve prepared the future civil rights movement in a really wonderful way .
they didn &apos;t think about it that way , but what they did for us was great .
so what happened years after that ?
for example , women who were asking for voting , the concept of founding fathers , which says that anatomical common importance is more important than the anatomical difference , and they said , &quot; we have a uterus and eggs as a difference , that we shouldn &apos;t have the right to vote , the right to own property , etc . &quot;
and women argued that was successful .
next came the successful civil rights movement , where we saw people like as sock reflector , who spach over it , &quot; am i not a woman ? &quot;
we find men in the marching rows of citizens &apos; movement saying , &quot; i &apos;m a man . &quot;
again , people have different skin colors that are based on anatomical similarities with anatomical differences , again , successfully .
we see the same thing in the disabled legal movement .
of course , the problem is that , as we start looking at all the similarities , we need to start questioning why we sustain certain separations .
well , remember , i want to sustain certain separations , anatomically , in our culture .
i don &apos;t want to give you fish the same rights as a human being .
i don &apos;t want to say that we should take away from anatomy .
i don &apos;t want to say that five year-olds should be the right to give their understanding of sex or marriage .
so there are some anatomical separations that make sense to me , and that we think we should keep .
but the challenge is to try to figure out which ones are and why we keep them and whether they &apos;re meaningful .
so let &apos;s go back to these two creatures that have been caught at the beginning of the talk .
we &apos;ve had two creatures , both in the mid-1979 , on exactly the same day .
let &apos;s imagine that one of them , maria , three months of spring , were born , so she &apos;s born on june 1 , 1980 .
heinrich , on the other hand , is born to the birthday , so he &apos;s born on march one , 1980 .
just because of the fact that maria was born three months old , she requires all kinds of rights three months before heinrich -- the right to take sex , the right to choose to drink , the right to drink .
heinrich has to wait for all of this , not because he actually has a different biological age , just because of the time point of his birth .
we find other oddities about what their rights are .
heinrich , since you think he &apos;s male -- although i didn &apos;t tell you he &apos;s with xy -- because you think he &apos;s male , he can now be drawn in , which maria doesn &apos;t have to worry about .
whereas in all states , maria can &apos;t perceive the same right thing that heinrich has in all states , and that is the right to marry .
heinrich can marry a woman in every state , but maria can marry a woman in a few states today .
so we have these permanent anatomical categories that are problematic and questionable in many ways .
and for me , the question is , what are we going to do because our science is making such progress in anatomy , that we &apos;re going to have to reach a point where we need to admit that a democracy that &apos;s based on anatomy could fall apart ?
i don &apos;t want to give up science , but at the same time it feels like science is self-assembling .
so where do we go ?
it seems like our culture is taking a kind of pragmatic posture : &quot; well , we need to pull a line somewhere , so we pull it somewhere . &quot;
but a lot of people are trapped in a very strange position .
so for example , texas decided at one point that to marry a man means you don &apos;t have a y chromosome , and a woman to marry means you had a y chromosome .
now in practice , people are not tested on their chromosome .
but it &apos;s also very bizarre because of the story i told you about the androgen receptor defect at the beginning .
if we look at one of the founding fathers of modern democracy , dr. martin luther king , he offers us in his &quot; i have a dream of speech . &quot;
he says we should judge people not &quot; their skin color , &quot; but &quot; judge them by the trait of their character , &quot; and go beyond anatomy .
and i want to say , &quot; yeah , that sounds like a really good idea . &quot;
but how do you do that in practice ?
how do you judge people because of their character ?
i also want to point out that i &apos;m not sure we should distribute rights in terms of people such a way , because i have to admit that i know a series of golden retriever that probably deserves more than some of the people i know .
i want to say that i probably know some light labradordogs , who are more able , more intelligent and more mature decisions to make their sexual relationships than some 40-year-old relations i know .
so how do we operate the question of the character ?
it turns out it &apos;s really hard .
and part of me is , what if the content of a personality was something that would be machine readable in the future -- using the fmri could be made visible ?
do we really want to go this way ?
i &apos;m not sure where we &apos;re going .
what i know is that it seems to be really important to think about the idea that the united states is leading to making thoughts about democracy .
in our effort for democracy , we &apos;ve done our thing really well , and i think we &apos;d do our thing well in the future .
we don &apos;t have the situation , as is the case in iran , where a man who feels sexually drawn to other men is punished with death , unless he &apos;s willing to sign himself a gender transformation in which case he can stay alive .
we don &apos;t exist with these kinds of states .
i &apos;m glad to say we don &apos;t have these states -- a surgeon i talked to a few years ago who had brought some siamese twins in them to separate them , partly to make a name .
but when i telephones with him , and i asked him why he did these interventions -- it was high-risk surgeries -- his answer was that in his country , these kids would be treated very badly , and that &apos;s why he had to do it .
i answered him , &quot; now did you consider political asyl rather than an operation to separate them ? &quot;
the united states has incredible ways to allow people to be the ones they are without having to change for the state &apos;s will .
so i think we need to be leaders .
well , just to end , i want to notice that i &apos;ve talked a lot about the fathers a lot .
and i want to think about the ways that democracy might look , or could have looked like , if we had involved mothers more .
and i want to say something that &apos;s radical for a feminist , and that is , i think , that there could be different kinds of insights that master anatomy , especially when people apply a group thinking .
for years , because i &apos;ve been interested in intersexuality , i &apos;ve been also interested in research in gender differences .
and one of the things that i found really interesting is the difference between men and women in terms of how they think and act in the world .
what we &apos;ve learned from cross-cultural studies is that women , on average -- not each , but on average -- tend to give a lot of complex social relationships and care to people who are vulnerable within the group , pay a lot of attention .
and so when we think about it , we have an interesting situation to do it .
years ago , when i was a graduate student , one of my students asked me to do my interest in feminism -- i thought of myself as a feminist , i do it that way -- a really strange question .
he said , &quot; tell me what &apos;s female about feminism . &quot;
and i thought , &quot; well , that &apos;s the most stupid question i &apos;ve ever heard .
feminism is about resolving cotypes about gender , so feminism is not female .
but the more i thought about his question , the more i thought there could be something female in feminism .
that &apos;s to say , there could be something on average , which is different from male brains , which makes us more aware of highly complex social relationships , and to make us more aware of the protective need .
so where the founding fathers were extremely suspicious of figuring out how individuals could be protected from the state , it &apos;s possible that if we put more mothers into this concept , we would get more of a concept , not just how to protect them , but how to care for each other .
and maybe it &apos;s where we have to go in the future when we take democracy out about anatomy -- think less about the individual body in terms of identity , and think more about relationships .
so that if we as a people are trying to make a more perfect connection , we think about what we can do for each other .
