as an artist , i think i &apos;m very important about context .
through my work , i &apos;m trying to express that people are not separate from nature , and that everything is connected .
the first time i was in antarctica , almost 10 years ago , where i saw my first icebergs .
i &apos;m awe of access .
my heart raced , i was dizzy , trying to write what was going on in front of me .
the icebergs around me were almost 60 meters out of the water , and i could only wonder that was a snowflake on another snowflake , year after year .
icebergs are born as a glacier &apos;s calf , or by breaking out of ice sheets .
every iceberg has its own individual personality .
they interact in clearly their environment and their experiences .
some people refuse to give up and brainer to the bitter end , while others don &apos;t stop and collapse in a seizure of dramatic passion .
when you look at an iceberg , you think they &apos;re slightly isolated , separated and alone , just like we humans often see .
but the truth is far from it .
as a iceberg melts , i breathe its ancient atmosphere .
during the iceberg , he releases mineral drinking water that feeds a lot of life forms .
i think of my footage of these icebergs as if i make portraits of my ancestors , in the mind that they exist in these individual moments , that they will never exist again .
it &apos;s not a death when they melt ; it &apos;s not an end , but it &apos;s a continuation of their path along the life cycle .
part of the ice in the icebergs that i &apos;m imaging is very young -- a few thousand years old .
and part of the ice is more than 100,000 years old .
the last pictures i &apos;d like to show you are an iceberg that i took pictures in kekertsuatsiak in greenland .
