this is a representation of your brain . your brain can be divided into two half .
that &apos;s the left half , which is the logical side , and then the right half , which is the intuitive side .
if we had a scale to measure the aptitudes of every hemisphere , we could show your brain .
for example , this would be somebody who &apos;s completely logical .
that would be somebody who &apos;s completely intuitive .
now , where would you position your brain at this scale ?
some of us may have decided for one of these extremes , but i think for most people in the audience , their brain looks something like this -- with a high aptitute that &apos;s at the same time in both hemisphere .
it &apos;s not like they &apos;re both exclusive or something .
they can be logical and intuitive .
and so i think of myself as one of the people , along with most other experimental quantum physicists , who need a good deal of logic to put together the complex ideas .
but at the same time , we need a good percentage of intuition to actually do the experiments .
how do we develop that intuition ? well , we love to play with things .
so we go out and play with it and then we see how it responds , and then we start to develop our intuition .
they basically do the same thing .
so one of the intuitions they &apos;ve developed over the years is probably that one thing at a time can only be in one place .
i mean , it can sound strange to think that one thing is in two different places at the same time , but they weren &apos;t born with this idea , they developed it .
i remember seeing a child play on a ground threshold .
he was another little kid , and he wasn &apos;t very good at it , and he was constantly falling .
but i bet that he taught him to play with the ground threshold a very valuable lesson , which is that the big things don &apos;t just leave you behind and they stay in one place .
and this is a great conceptual model of the world , as long as they &apos;re not particle physicists .
it would be a terrible model for a particle physicist because they don &apos;t play with bodily pigs , they play with these little strange particles .
and when they play with their particles , they find all kinds of strange things -- like they fly right through walls , or that at the same time they can be in two different places .
and so they wrote down all these observations , and they called them the theory of quantum mechanics .
this was the state of physics a few years ago ; it took quantum mechanics to describe the little , tiny particles .
but it didn &apos;t take them to describe the great everyday objects around us .
that didn &apos;t like my intuition , and maybe just because i don &apos;t play with particles so often .
well , i sometimes play with them , but not very often .
and i &apos;ve never seen them .
i mean , nobody has ever seen one particle .
but my logical side didn &apos;t like it either .
because if all of these things are made up of particles and all of these particles follow the rules of quantum mechanics , shouldn &apos;t just follow the rules of quantum mechanics ?
i don &apos;t see a reason why that shouldn &apos;t be .
so i would feel better about all of this , if we could somehow show that everyday objects also follow the rules of quantum mechanics .
so a few years ago , i went to do that .
i created one .
this is the first object you can see that was in quantum mechanical superposition .
so what we &apos;re looking at here is a tiny computer chip .
and you can see that green dot there in the middle .
this is the piece of metal i &apos;m going to talk about in a minute .
this is a picture of the object .
here i &apos;m losing it a little bit . we &apos;re looking at the center .
and here &apos;s a really big close-up of this little piece of metal .
so what we &apos;re looking at is a little piece of metal that &apos;s shaped like a springboard , and it &apos;s over the edge .
so i made this thing in a similar way that you make a computer chip .
i went to a clean room with new silium slices , and i raced on all the big devices for 100 hours .
for the last little bit , i had to build my own machine -- to get this kind of swimming pool and shaped hole and get this thing .
this thing has the ability to be in the quantum mechanical superposition , but it takes a little bit of help to do it .
look , let me give you an analogy .
you know how uncomfortable it is to be in a full elevator ?
i mean , when i &apos;m alone in the elevator , i do all kinds of strange things , but then other people go up , and i listen to all these things because i don &apos;t want to harm them with it , or , frankly , they go away .
so quantum mechanics says unmoving objects feel the same .
the fellow drivers for inmobile objects are not just people , but also the light that shines on them , and the wind that passes to them and the heat of space .
and so we knew that if we wanted this piece of metal to behave quantum mechanically , we had to throw all the passengers out .
and then we did .
we turned off the light , put it in a vacuum and sucked out all the air , and cooled it up until almost now , all alone in the elevator , the piece of metal was free to behave as it wanted .
so we measured his movement .
we found that it &apos;s really strange .
instead of just being quiet there , it vibrated , the way it vibrated was something like this -- like a more expanding and together parenting bubble .
in which we gave him a little push , we could make it vibrate at the same time , not vibrate -- something that &apos;s only allowed in quantum mechanics .
so what i &apos;m going to tell you right now is what &apos;s really fantastic .
what does it mean for an object to vibrate at the same time , not vibrate ?
let &apos;s think about the atoms .
so the first case : all the trillion atoms that are made of are still there , and at the same time the same atoms are moving up and down .
just at precise times , you agree .
they &apos;re delocalized for the rest of the time .
that means that every atom at the same time is in two different places , which means that the whole piece of metal is in two different places .
i think that &apos;s really cool .
really .
that was worth closing in the clean space for all this year , because , check that , the mass difference between a single atom and that piece of metal is about the same as the difference between the piece of metal and you .
so if a single atom can be in two different places at the same time , this piece of metal can be in two different places , why not you ?
i mean , that &apos;s just what my logical side says .
so , imagine if you were in many places at the same time , how would that feel ?
how would your mind bend up being delocalized in the space ?
there &apos;s another aspect of history .
when we warmed it up , turned on the light and looked at the box , we saw that the piece of metal was always there in a piece .
and so i had to develop this new intuition that it looks like all the objects in the elevator are actually just torture objects that are made together in a small space .
you hear a lot of talk about how quantum mechanics say that everything is connected to everything .
well , that &apos;s not quite right .
there &apos;s more to it , it &apos;s even deeper .
it &apos;s like these connections , their connections with all the things around them , are literally defining who they are , and that &apos;s the profound and strange of quantum mechanics .
thank you .
in 2007 , i decided that we should conceptualize how we think about economic development .
it should be our goal that if families think about where they live and want to work , they &apos;re given the opportunity to choose between at least one hand full of different cities all standing in competition for new residents .
we &apos;re right now far from that goal .
there are billions of people in developing countries who are not even available to a single city that would welcome them .
but the amazing thing about cities is that they &apos;re worth so much more than it costs them to build .
so we could make the world very easy with dumb , maybe even hundreds of new cities .
now this may sound absurd for you , as far as you &apos;ve never thought about new cities .
but they &apos;re just trading out apartments against cities .
imagine half of the people who want to live in apartments did this already ; half of the people don &apos;t yet .
you could try to expand the capacity of the apartments that existed .
but you know what you &apos;re going to be insisting on , in these apartments and their environment , there are laws to avoid being complained and deflect from exposure .
so it turns out it &apos;s very difficult to come up with all these extensions .
but you could go to a whole new place , build a whole new block , assuming the laws there would support you to build and not prevent it .
so i &apos;ve proposed that governments create new areas that provide enough space for a city and have given them a name : charter cities .
i found out later that , for example , around the same time , jafour and octavio have thought about the challenge of a reform in honduras .
they knew that every year about 75,000 hondurans could leave their country to go out to the united states , and they wanted to know what they could do to make sure that these people could stay in their country and do exactly the same in honduras .
at this point , jafour said to octavio , &quot; what happens if we take an unsettled area of our country -- what if we just give them a message -- part of the american embassy ; part of the canadian bottleneck -- and if people want to go to work under the canadian rules or the united states , can they work there , and can do everything they would have to go to canada or america on the surface of these messages ? &quot;
