photos like this : a building site along a much more driving road .
but it has an unexpected twist .
and still keep a realistic level .
or photos like this -- dark and colorful at the same time , but everybody with the common goal of keeping a realistic level .
when i say reality , i mean photoreality .
because , of course , it &apos;s not something you can really capture , but i always want to make it look like she could have , in a photograph .
photos where you have to think for a moment to figure out the trick .
so it &apos;s more about capturing an idea than really a moment .
but what &apos;s the trick that makes it look realistic ?
is this about the details or the colors ?
is it about light ?
what creates the illusion ?
sometimes the illusion is illusion .
but finally , it &apos;s about how we interpret the world , and how it can be made on a two-dimensional surface .
it &apos;s not about what &apos;s realistic , it &apos;s about what we think is realistic .
so i think the foundations are very simple .
i think of them as a puzzle of reality where you can take different pieces and put them together to create an alternative reality .
and let me show you a simple example .
we have three perfectly imaginable physical objects that we can all identify with in a three-dimensional world .
but in a certain way , you can create something that still looks three-dimensional as if it could exist .
but at the same time , we know that this is not possible .
so we overlist our brains , because our brains just don &apos;t accept that it doesn &apos;t really make sense .
and i see the same process in combining photos .
it &apos;s really just about combining different realities .
so the things that make a picture look realistic , i think they &apos;re the things we don &apos;t think about , the things around us in our everyday lives .
but if we combine photos , it &apos;s really important to think about it , because otherwise , they just look wrong .
so i would say that there are three simple rules to follow to make a realistic outcome .
as you can see , these are not three special images .
but you can combine something special like this .
so the first rule is that combined photos should have the same perspective .
secondly , photos should have the same kind of lighting .
and these two pictures meet these two demands -- shot at the same altitude and the same kind of lighting .
third , it &apos;s about making it impossible to tell where the individual images start and end by connecting them seamlessly .
make it impossible to say how the photograph was actually put together .
so by comparing color , contrast and brightness to the edges to individual images , photographic deprivation , like field depth , unseen colors and disorders , we wipe the boundaries between the different images and let them look like a single photograph , even though a picture can basically contain hundreds of levels .
here &apos;s another example .
