my role is to explain to people how wonderful the new technologies that have come up will be . and i thought , since i &apos;m here among friends , i would tell you what i really think . and also try to look back and understand what &apos;s really happening here with these incredible jumps forward that are so fast that we can barely keep up .
i &apos;m going to start showing you a single boring slide for a moment .
... could you show the slide for a moment ?
this is a slide i randomly chose from my folder .
i &apos;m not talking about the details of the slide , but rather the general shape .
this slide shows data from an analysis of us about risc processors &apos; performance compared to the performance of a local area network .
what &apos;s interesting here is that this slide , like so some of the others we often meet in our field , are a kind of semi-logarithmic curve .
in other words , every step here is a power in the scale .
and this is a novelty that we need to use this guy scale on semi-logarithmic curves in the field of technology .
something very strange is happening here .
this is basically what i &apos;m going to talk about .
so if you could turn on the light again .
a little brighter because i &apos;m going to draw something on paper here in a minute .
now , why do we draw graphs in technology on semi-logarithmic curves ?
the reason for that is , if i drew it on a normal curve , where , say , these are the years , so the timeline of a way , and this is any measure of the technology i want to show with a graph , the graph will be silly .
they then look like this .
and that doesn &apos;t tell us much .
now , if i want to record another technology , say , a transportation technology , it would be very irrational on the semi-logarithmic scale .
but if something like this happens , it changes the qualitative circumstances .
so if transportation technology were to move as fast as the microprocessor technology was to move forward , we could get in a taxi tomorrow and in 30 seconds we would be in tokyo .
but that &apos;s not so fast .
this has never been done before in the history of technology development , this kind of recursive growth where the scale is exponentially increasing every few years .
the question i want to ask you now is , if you look at these exponential curves , you see , they don &apos;t go on forever .
it &apos;s not possible that everything is evolving forever and forever as fast as it is now .
there are two ways .
either it becomes a classic s-curve like this , until something completely new comes in , or it will happen here .
it &apos;s about this .
well , i &apos;m an optimist , so i think something like this will happen .
is that really true , then that means we &apos;re in the middle of a transition right now .
we &apos;re on this line here , in a transition from the world to a new kind of world .
so the question i want to ask , and i also often ask myself , is how this new world will be ?
what &apos;s this new state that &apos;s starting to take on the world ?
because the transition seems to be very , very confusing if you &apos;re in the middle .
when i was a child , the future was somewhere in 2000 , and people often talked about what would happen in 2000 .
now we have a conference here where people talk about the future , and you realize the future is still in the year 2000 .
we &apos;re not going to go further than that .
so in other words , the future has shrinked by a year since i &apos;m in the world .
i think the reason for that is that we realize that anything is going on .
the transition happens . we can all feel it .
and we know right now that it just doesn &apos;t make sense to try to look 30 or 50 years into the future , because everything will be so different that a simple wedding of what we &apos;re doing now just doesn &apos;t make sense of it .
i want to talk about what that might be , that transition we &apos;re in right now .
to do that , i &apos;m going to first talk about some of the other things that really have nothing to do with technology or computers .
because i think to really understand this , we need to go back and look at the thing on a longer scale of time .
and that is , i want to look at this on the earth &apos;s scale of life .
i think the whole picture makes sense if you divide it into a few billion steps .
so let &apos;s go back , 2.5 billion years . the earth was a big , sterile stone clump with a lot of chemicals floating on it .
now if you look at the way these chemicals were organized , it gives us a pretty good picture of how they did it .
i also think there are theories that start to understand how everything started with rna , but i &apos;m going to tell you a simplified story of this , which is that at that time , there were little oil droplet flowing around , which had different kinds of recipes for chemicals .
some of these oil droplet contain a special combination of chemicals that allowed them to integrate other chemicals from outside , and so on .
all of them were like this started to divide .
these little oil droplet were the most primitive cell form .
but these oil droplet were not about alive in the current sense , because each of them was just a small random recipe of chemicals .
and every time it divided , they &apos;ve spread to inexorable chemicals .
so every droplet was a little different .
in fact , the droplet that grew up growing more optimal composition than others , and integrated more and more chemicals from outside and divided faster .
so these tends to survive longer , and they multiplied at a greater rate .
so this is just a very simple chemical form of life , but more interesting , when these droplet learned a trick about abstraction .
in any way we don &apos;t quite understand , these droplet have learned the ability to write down information .
they learned to store the recipe of the cell as information , and that is in a certain chemical form that we call dna .
in other words , they found a way in this hostile , evolutionary way that allowed them to write down what they were made of , so that this information could be stored and copied .
the amazing thing about this is that storing this kind of information over the course of 2.5 billion years that it came out stayed the same .
in fact , the recipe for us , which is our genes , from exactly the same code and the same writing .
and every living thing uses exactly the same letters and the same code .
we &apos;re so far that , just for fun , we can write things about this code ourselves .
and i have 100 micrograms of a white pulver here that i &apos;m trying to keep in airports from security staff .
there &apos;s -- what i &apos;ve done is i &apos;ve taken this code -- the code is made up of normal letters that we use for symbolizing -- and i &apos;ve written my business card on a piece of dna and i &apos;ve amplified it 10 22 times .
so if somebody wants a hundred million copies of my business card , i have enough for anyone in this room and even for everybody in the world , and it &apos;s right here .
if i had been actually a selfish , i would have written it on a virus and released it into space .
so what &apos;s the next step ?
the signing of dna was an interesting step .
and that &apos;s what made these cells -- that &apos;s what made them happy for another billion years .
but then another very interesting step where things became completely different , which is to start communicating and trading information so that communities could come from cells .
i don &apos;t know if you knew that , but bacteria can actually exchange their dna .
that &apos;s why , for example , consistency is growing into antibiotics .
some bacteria have figured out how to stay away from penicillin and have written that information with other bacteria into the dna , and now we have a lot of bacteria that are resistant to penicillin because the bacteria communicate with each other .
now this communication allowed communities to be able to happen , in a way , in the same boat ; they were synergetic .
so they either survived together , or they went down together , which meant that if a community was successful , all the individuals in the community were more often repeated and preferred by evolution .
the transition point is now where these communities are so close together that they decided to write the recipe for the whole community into a sign chain on dna .
and the next interesting stage took about another billion years .
at that point , we have multi-cellular communities , communities of many different cell types , which act together as a single organism .
in fact , we &apos;re also such a multi-celled community .
we have a lot of cells that are no longer put on their own .
your skin cells are useless without heart cells , muscle cells , brain cells and so on .
so these communities started to evolve , so that the level in which evolution happened was no longer the individual cell , but the whole cell community that we call organism .
the next step was now happening within these communities .
the cell communities started to abstract information again .
and they developed special structures that did nothing but process information within the organism .
and these are the neural structures .
so the neurons are the information processing system that these cell communities have built .
they started educating specialists within the community , special structures , which were responsible for learning , understanding and holding information .
and this was the brain and the nervous system of these communities .
this gave them an evolutionary advantage .
because at that point , an individual -- learning has now happened within the time of a single organism &apos;s lifespan , rather than about this evolutionary period .
so for example , an organism could learn not to eat a certain fruit because it tasted bad and made it sick that last time he ate it .
this could now happen within the lifetime of a single organism , whereas hundreds of thousands of years before that were taken , because this information had to be learned evolutionary by the individuals who died because of this fruit , because these information processing structures were not there .
so the nervous system has the evolutionary process using these special information structures because evolution could now happen within an individual .
it could happen within a time-learning framework .
what happened then is that the individual organisms found a way to communicate with each other .
let &apos;s give you an example , the most sophisticated version of this kind of communication is the human language .
it &apos;s a pretty amazing invention when you think about it .
i have a very complicated , disordered and confused idea in my head .
i &apos;m sitting here giving basically gruesome sounds of mine , hoping to create a similar confused idea in your head that has a certain similarity to my original idea .
so we take something very complicated , we turn it into sound , a sequence of sound , and we produce something very complicated in the minds of others .
so this allows us to work again as a unified organism .
and what we actually did , we , humanity , is we started to abstract .
we go through the same levels that several cell organisms have gone through -- the abstraction of our methods of holding data on , presenting .
for example , the invention of language was a small step in that direction .
telephones , computers , video obligations , cd-roms and so on are all our specialized mechanisms that we built in our community to be able to handle this information .
and it connects all of us together to something that &apos;s much bigger , and also able to evolve faster than we &apos;ve been .
so today , evolution can happen in the time period of microseconds .
you also saw tys &apos;s little evolutionary example , where he showed some evolution in the convoltation program , right in front of your eyes .
so now we &apos;ve faded the time scales again .
the first steps in the story i told you took a billion years to play .
the next steps , like the nervous system and the brain , took a few hundred million years .
then the next steps , like language and so on , took less than a million years .
and these next steps , like electronics , seem to take just a few decades .
so the process feeds itself , and i think auto-catalyzing is the word for it -- when something increases its speed of change .
the more it changes , the faster it changes .
and i think that &apos;s what we see here in this explosive curve .
we see the process that feeds on itself .
i live professionally from building computers , and i know that i could not use the mechanism that i use to build computers without the recent advances in computer technology .
my current work is to design objects with such a high complexity that it &apos;s impossible for me to design them in the traditional sense .
i don &apos;t know what every single transistor is doing in the connection machine .
it has billions of them .
what i do instead , and whatever designers of thinking machines do , is we think at a certain abstraction level , we overgive that to the machine , and the machine does something that overgoes our skills better and faster than we could ever do it ourselves .
and it does it in part with the ways we don &apos;t even understand it right now .
one way that &apos;s particularly interesting , and which i &apos;ve used a lot of times recently , is evolution itself .
and we &apos;re installing an evolutionary process in the machine that &apos;s going on in the microsecond area .
to give you an example , in the most extreme cases , we can create a program that evolves from random instructions .
we say , &quot; computers , please generate a hundred million randomly selected sequences of instructions .
now please do all of these randomly chosen instructions , do all the programs , and finally choose those who are next to my giving . &quot;
so in other words , i define first what i want .
let &apos;s say i want to sorrow numbers , which is a simple example i &apos;ve already used .
so find programs that can most care about numbers .
of course , the chance with randomly chosen instructions is very small that they &apos;re sorting numbers by accident , so probably none of the instructions are actually going to do this .
but one of them , with some luck , likes to put two numbers in the right order .
now i say , &quot; computers , now take the 10 percent of the sequences that came to mind .
store them off , delete the rest .
now all the rest of the limbs that have best cared about numbers .
and that is , with a way of recombining , analog to restoring . &quot;
take two programs , and they produce children through the exchange of their subroutines , and the kids inherit the features of the subroutines of the two programs .
so now i have a new generation of programs that have come from combining programs that have come a little closer to the preventions than others .
say , &quot; please repeat this process . &quot;
rating them again .
lead maybe some mutations .
and i &apos;ll try the whole thing again with another generation .
all of these generations need just a few milliseconds .
and so i can go through evolution in the computer within a few minutes , or more complicated cases , a few hours .
finally , i get programs that can perfectly sorrow numbers .
