it may seem strange to you , but i &apos;m a big fan of concrete blockages .
the first concrete blocks were made in 1868 and devised a simple idea : module from cement with determined measurements that fit together .
concrete building blocks became the most used building unit in the world very quickly .
they put us in the position of building things that were bigger than us , buildings , bridges , one stone at a time .
basically , the concrete building block had become the building block of our time .
almost a hundred years later , in 1947 , lego came out with this .
it was called the automatically connected rock .
and within a few years , lego moved into every household .
it &apos;s been estimated that over 400 billion rocks were produced -- or 75 rocks for every person on the planet .
they don &apos;t have to be an engineer to create beautiful houses , beautiful bridges or beautiful buildings .
lego made it possible for everyone .
lego has basically taken the concrete building block , the building block of the world , and made it a building block for our imagination .
in the meantime , at bell labs , the next revolution was announced , the next building block .
the transistor was a little plastic unit that would bring us from a world of static , interconnected building blocks to a world where everything was going to be interactive .
like the concrete block , the transistor allows us to build much larger , more complex cycles , one stone at a time .
but there &apos;s a big difference : the transistor was just experts .
i personally accept that the building block of our time is reserved for experts , and so i decided to change that .
eight years ago , i was at the media lab , and i started to explore this idea of how to put the power of engineers in the hands of artists and designers .
a few years ago , i started developing little-life .
let me show you how they work .
littingness is electronic module that has specific function .
they &apos;re preferred to be light , sound , engine and sensor .
and the best part is that they connect with magnets .
so you can &apos;t put them wrong .
the stones are colored .
green is output , blue is electricity , pink is input , and orange is cables .
so all you have to do is connect a blue and a green one , and you can build very quickly larger circles .
they put a blue one on a green one , and they can make light .
they can put a switch in between , and so they &apos;ve created a little dimmer .
take out the switch to put out a pulsmodule , which is here , and they made a little blind .
add that buzzer for an extra effect , and they &apos;ve made a noise machine .
i &apos;m going to stop that .
beyond the simple game , littlife is actually quite powerful .
instead of coding , wiring or solving , littviits allows them to code with simple , intuitive gestures .
so to accelerate or slow the flash , just turn on this button , and it makes the impulse faster or slower .
the idea behind littviits is that it &apos;s a growing library .
we want to put every single interaction in the world into a useful rock .
lights , sound , solar elements , motors -- everything should be available .
we &apos;ve distributed little-life to children , and you can see them playing with it .
and it was an incredible experience .
the most beautiful thing is , how do you start to understand the electronics that surround you in everyday life and that you don &apos;t learn in school ?
how , for example , a night light works , or why the doors of the elevator stay open , or how an ipod responds to touch .
we also brought little-life to design schools .
so for example , we had designers with no experience in electronic things that started playing with littviits as a material .
here we see , with filming , paper and water bottles , like georges ...
a few weeks ago , we brought littviits at risd , and we gave them to some designers who had no technical experience -- just cardboard , wood and paper -- and told them , &quot; do something . &quot;
here &apos;s an example of a project they did , a movable confetti cannon .
but wait , this is really my favorite project .
it &apos;s a play-dough hummer that &apos;s afraid in the dark .
for these non-engineers , littviits became another material , electronics just became another material .
and we want to make this material available to all of them .
so littviits is open source .
you can go to the website , download all the design curtains and make them yourself .
we want the world of creators , the inventors , the contributors , because this world we live in , this interactive world , belongs to us .
so , go ahead and start inventing them .
thank you .
